The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, July 04, 2004 				 Sonia meets Singh on budget
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, July 3: Congress president Sonia Gandhi met Prime Minister Manmohan Singh late last night, a day after returning to the capital from a five-day private visit to Uttaranchal, to take stock of the political situation days before the United Progressive Alliance government presents its maiden budget.																								The two leaders discussed  at the Prime Ministers 7, Race Course Road official residence  the shape and contents of the budget that finance minister P. Chidambaram will present on July 8, Congress sources said.																								Sonia, who heads the National Advisory Council set up to oversee implementation of the ruling coalitions common minimum programme, is believed to have recently given Singh a note spelling out the UPAs budget priorities. Sources said the note advised the government to focus on the agricultural sector, employment generation, education and health care.																								The two leaders also discussed the partys political strategy for the ensuing resumed session of Parliament, the sources said. The discussion, they added, was a precursor to the consultations among UPA partners.																								The meeting comes in the backdrop of intense speculation in the party that Singh might effect a minor expansion of his five-week-old ministry to induct some Congress nominees. 
